00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:16.170
from the house of representatives

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:19.870
and the house has a very different set of
rules and atmosphere then you have historically

00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:21.190
found in the senate

00:13:21.190 --> 00:13:25.380
my colleagues from the house can speak more
directly to this but the party line voting

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:27.740
and the all-or-nothing philosophy

00:13:27.740 --> 00:13:30.030
it permeates the house of representatives

00:13:30.030 --> 00:13:32.620
has not been a part of the senate dynamic

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:34.610
until very recently

00:13:34.610 --> 00:13:38.620
believe it or not this is also the first time
in the entire fifty years

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:41.310
since the graduation of the class of fifty
four

00:13:41.310 --> 00:13:45.119
that the republican party has been in control
of both the white house and the senate

00:13:45.119 --> 00:13:46.800
and the house of representatives

00:13:46.800 --> 00:13:49.819
and an overwhelming majority of the federal judiciary

00:13:49.819 --> 00:13:50.890
has been appointed

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:53.630
by the republican administration

00:13:53.630 --> 00:13:56.920
often in those fifty years democrats had control

00:13:56.920 --> 00:14:00.930
but on those occasions it was never a significant
strain on the system

00:14:00.930 --> 00:14:07.780
of checks and balances because democratic
unity is such an unusual phenomenon

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:09.660
as the saying goes

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:11.940
we tend to line up in a circle

00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:18.940
when we try to form a firing squad

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:21.340
the checks and balances

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:25.240
are less effective when the party in control
is more monolithic

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:28.020
the only real check on a bad idea today

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:29.920
it's a filibuster in the senate

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:33.910
the challenge is especially serious when the
pressure from the right is so determined

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:36.949
to extend its control to the judicial branch
of the government

00:14:36.949 --> 00:14:38.750
as well

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:42.030
fortunately we have an election every two
years they can restore

00:14:42.030 --> 00:14:44.680
the balance when the strain is too severe

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:47.680
I think of Winston Churchill often these
days

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:51.400
Democracy is the worst form of government
except for all the others that have been tried

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:53.420
from time to time

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:57.300
if it could transform thirteen tiny quarreling
colonies

00:14:57.300 --> 00:14:59.890
into a free nation two hundred years ago

00:14:59.890 --> 00:15:03.430
if it could transform Europe and Japan after
world war two

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:05.860
and bring down the Berlin Wall as well

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:08.929
it can also produced good to the many
challenges

00:15:08.929 --> 00:15:12.650
that we face today at home and around
the world.

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:14.450
I'm an optimist though,

00:15:14.450 --> 00:15:17.350
I like to think that the times are auspicious,

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:22.210
that we can tap into the wave of new hope
and commitments stirring in the country now

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:26.380
after the very moving dedication of the world
war two memorial a week ago

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:29.200
the sixtieth anniversary of D-DAY

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:32.050
we are all in this together

00:15:32.050 --> 00:15:33.340
the greed

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:34.850
the special interests

00:15:34.850 --> 00:15:36.649
the petty partisan passions

00:15:36.649 --> 00:15:38.860
the poison politics

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:40.550
can't endlessly stop an idea

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:42.540
who's time has come.

00:15:42.540 --> 00:15:46.189
again Churchill said it best, America will
do the right thing

00:15:46.189 --> 00:15:51.210
after it's tried everything else

00:15:51.210 --> 00:15:52.830
legislating is not exactly

00:15:52.830 --> 00:15:54.920
instant gratification

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:58.970
in the sixties as a young Senator I was drawn
to the issue of civil rights education and

00:15:58.970 --> 00:15:59.620
health care

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:01.010
and I still am

00:16:01.010 --> 00:16:03.990
and Harvard’s been an indispensable resource

00:16:03.990 --> 00:16:06.830
you can assemble the best minds on any
issue

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:10.640
and then try to form a coalition of the willing
to fight for it.

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:13.350
usually you have to sustain some losses and
then regroup

00:16:13.350 --> 00:16:15.970
we you can come back to fight again

00:16:15.970 --> 00:16:19.650
most of the real gains and policies happen
that way

00:16:19.650 --> 00:16:20.830
incrementally

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:23.250
nothing happens if you let the best

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:25.030
become the enemy of the good

00:16:25.030 --> 00:16:28.920
we've been struggling for two hundred years
to fulfill the promise of equal opportunity

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:30.050
for all

00:16:30.050 --> 00:16:33.940
the year the class of fifty four graduated
was the year of the modern revolution in

00:16:33.940 --> 00:16:35.050
civil rights began

00:16:35.050 --> 00:16:37.579
with the landmark school desegregation decision

00:16:37.579 --> 00:16:39.370
by the supreme court

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:41.380
we've made progress since then

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:44.090
but we know that civil rights is still the
unfinished business

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:45.290
of America

00:16:45.290 --> 00:16:48.959
in education we began to argue in congress
the sixties about aid

00:16:48.959 --> 00:16:51.730
to low-income students and high poverty districts

00:16:51.730 --> 00:16:53.160
and we still are

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:58.299
and today we continue those battles and higher
education we still have glaring

00:16:58.299 --> 00:16:59.070
inequalities

00:16:59.070 --> 00:17:04.869
and qualified low-income students only a quarter
is likely to attend college as the more

00:17:04.869 --> 00:17:08.159
qualified but wealthy as equally qualified
or no more

00:17:08.159 --> 00:17:08.890
qualified than

00:17:08.890 --> 00:17:14.700
but wealthier fellow students
the GI bill for the world war two generation

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:16.020
wasn't early giant step

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:18.620
but we still have miles to go to close the gap

00:17:18.620 --> 00:17:19.840
The president 

00:17:19.840 --> 00:17:22.960
has announced an enormously interesting innovative
program

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:26.880
that any child that is basically
in the bottom third

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:32.980
of the economic income but is able to
meet the criteria are the standards here at

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:36.190
Harvard before the income from forty thousand
dollars less

00:17:36.190 --> 00:17:37.169
will not

00:17:37.169 --> 00:17:38.410
 have to pay

00:17:38.410 --> 00:17:41.510
 the tuition

00:17:41.510 --> 00:17:42.110
leading

00:17:42.110 --> 00:17:45.080
advance and in terms of colleges

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:48.350
that challenge other colleges 
across this country

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:51.110
health care policy is never easy either

00:17:51.110 --> 00:17:55.500
in nineteen fifty four we were just a few years
away from Harry Truman’s

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:57.950
unsuccessful effort to enact universal health
care

00:17:57.950 --> 00:17:59.530
still hasn't happened

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:02.060
even though every other industrial nation
the world did it

00:18:02.060 --> 00:18:03.720
years ago, made health care

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:05.630
a fundamental right for all

00:18:05.630 --> 00:18:07.430
we shouldn't be going it alone

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:08.800
on foreign policy

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:10.500
and we shouldn't be pretending

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:13.119
on health care that everyone is out of step

00:18:13.119 --> 00:18:20.119
but Uncle Same. let me

00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:26.700
when my brother Jack was in congress and senate

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:30.160
in the nineteen forties and fifties the senate
would recess

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:31.820
in June

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.020
for the rest of the year

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:38.050
some members spent more time on the links
of the burning tree country club

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:40.660
than on the floor the united states senate

00:18:40.660 --> 00:18:44.930
but with the seriousness of the issues on
civil rights and the war in Vietnam the senate

00:18:44.930 --> 00:18:45.410
changed

00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:47.650
to a five-day week

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:50.470
twelve month calendar with some votes

00:18:50.470 --> 00:18:53.490
being held between Christmas and new year's
day

00:18:53.490 --> 00:18:55.809
the challenges facing the country

00:18:55.809 --> 00:18:58.560
were too important to ignore

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:01.880
the time in actual session is shorter 
now

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:06.650
we don't get out in June but votes usually only
take place between Tuesdays and Thursdays

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:10.360
there are many more recesses than there used
to be and they are longer

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:14.270
but the problems that we're facing in our
country are as great

00:19:14.270 --> 00:19:17.700
as or greater than at any time in our nation's
history

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:19.839
and I believe that we will rise

00:19:19.839 --> 00:19:21.110
to meet them

00:19:21.110 --> 00:19:24.980
it took Lyndon Johnson’s landslide in nineteen
sixty four

00:19:24.980 --> 00:19:28.019
to make Medicare happen in nineteen sixty
five

00:19:28.019 --> 00:19:30.729
and a John Kerry landslide in two thousand four

00:19:30.729 --> 00:19:33.860
might just be what the doctor ordered for
two thousand five

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:34.410
thank you very much

